<br>
However, if you aren't afraid of asking a few questions, you can quickly find all the information that you want about the game, your role as a paladin, the best equipment to use, etc just by posting a few questions here.<br>
<br>
It seems that many lower level paladins have found this site, and lurk, rather than posting or asking anything.  I created <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub43.ezboard.com/bthelieutenants">The Lieutenants</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> in order to help out the lower level paladins, but unfortunately I don't really have the motivation to keep that site very active.<br>
<br>
My opinion is, paladins are fun to play at ALL levels.  As soon as you can get Ghoulbane, though, being a paladin becomes a real blast.  From Ghoulbane and Instrument of Nife all the way up to level 50 is a wild ride.  At 51 (where I'm at now) things seem to slow down considerably, but I still play my paladin over all 6 of my twinks.<br>
<br>
Oh, and one important thing.  There is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> HUGE</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> difference between a paladin and a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> well-played</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> paladin.  One can do some stuff.  The second can do almost anything in a well coordinated group.  Reading this site gives you the tools you need to be a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> well-played</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> paladin.  Whether or not the people on your server recognize the benefit of having a well-played paladin in their groups or not, you can certainly make a name for yourself by learning to play your class to the limit of its abilities. <p><div align="center"><font size="2">Aragir Lancot<BR>
